In the DB: Field `lock_version` (INT) must be set.

In model:

```
<?php
class User extends Eloquent {
    ...
    public static $optimistic_lock = true;
    ...
}
```

Use case: 

```
$user1 = User::find(1);
$user2 = User::find(1);

$user1->name = "foo";
$user1->save();

$user2->name ="bar";
$user2->save(); // should throw an exception
```
## Update:

It seems I have to give a more real world example, how useful this is: 

Imagine 2 (or more) people want to update the same record at the same time. So the browse to user/edit and get a form. In the form, we use the hidden field named `lock_version`. E.g. the lock_verson is 3 and was filled from the database. 

```
<input type="hidden" name="lock_version" value="{{$user->lock_version}}"/>
```

Now person 1 saves the changed user record, save() uses the id and lock_version to find the record where the changes are based on. Record was found and updated. lock_version is now 4. 

Person 2 changes the record too. The edit_action would look something like

```
...
public function action_edit($id)
    {
    if (! $user = User::find($id)) {
        $data['error'] = "User with id $id not found.";
        return View::make('user.index', $data);
    }

    if (Input::get()) {
        try {
            $user->fill(Input::get()); // here the version gets overwritten from the forms value!
            $user->save();
            return Redirect::to('user/list')->with('success','User ' . $user . ' updated.');
        } catch (Exception $e) {
            $data['error'] = $e->getMessage();
            $data['user'] = $user;
            return View::make('user.edit', $data);
        }
    }

    $data['user'] = $user;
    return View::make('user.edit', $data);
}
...
```

So you see the user data which we get using user->find() were overwritten, so was `lock_version`. It gets value 3 as in the hidden field of the form. save() can not update by `id=x` and `lock_version=3`.

The record was not found and can not be updated. So person 2 does not make unwanted overwrites. Person 2 changes are based on a outdated record. 

