With this change, it is now possible to authenticate a User with any parameters passed to login.

Before, it would have been impossible to implent a passwordless OpenID authentication. With this change, it is now possible to implement by having this closure:

```
'login' => function($id) {
    $i = Identity::where_OpenIDURL($id)->first();
    if ($i == NULL) {
        return false;
    }
    $u = $i->user;
    if ($u == NULL) {
        return false;
    }
    return $u;
},
```

This is for a db schema that looks like this:

```
    +-------------------+
    |       user        |
    +-------------------+
    | id        NUMERIC |
    | username  TEXT    |
    +-------------------+

    +--------------------+
    |     identities     |
    +--------------------+
    | id         NUMERIC |
    | OpenIDURL  TEXT    |
    | user_id    NUMERIC |
    +--------------------+
```

This allows a user to link different OpenID Identities (URLs) to a User and use any of them to log-in.

This is just an example.

Another use case I would have is to have the Authentication mechanism handled elsewhere. This could be for example a `.htaccess`-based authentication.

